<h1>@HI{{kai}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vplain{{}} (@HI{{no}}) <strong>@HI{{kai}}</strong>.
<li> @Ai{{}} (@HI{{no}}) <strong>@HI{{kai}}</strong>.
<li> @Anastem{{}} (@HI{{na no}}) <strong>@HI{{kai}}</strong>.
<li> @N{{}} (@HI{{na no}})<strong>@HI{{kai}}</strong>.
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{kai}}</strong> is a sentence ending particle which marks a "yes/no" question in informal male speech.
The preceding sentence must be in the plain form.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{kai}}</strong> is only used for "yes/no" questions. For sentences involving an interrogative,
<a href="grammar-particle-dai.html">@HI{{dai}}</a> is used.
</p>

<p>
In the sentence patterns above, the @HI{{no}} appears where formal speech would have used <a href="grammar-n-desu.html">@HI{{ndesu}}</a>.
</p>

<p>
The equivalent sentences in female informal speech would be formed by dropping <strong>@HI{{kai}}</strong> and using a rising intonation.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{day^book^word}}wo@KJ{{exertion^strong}}suru<strong>kai</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Will you study Japanese?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kono@KT{{apa-to}}ha@KJ{{quiet}}ka<strong>kai</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Is this apartment quiet?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{mister^accomplished}}ha@KJ{{study^life}}<strong>kai</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Are you students?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{sono@KJ{{book}}ha@KJ{{difficult}}shiino<strong>kai</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Is that book difficult?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ano@KJ{{person}}ha@KJ{{before^life}}nano<strong>kai</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Is that person a teacher?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

